body:
Emulator not opening inside the windows toolbar.


## Steps to Reproduce
1. I turned on "Launch in a tool window" in settings `Tools/Emulator`
2. Started the emulator using AVD window.
3. Instead of opening the emulator inside the toolbar(right toolbar), it is opening independently.

comment_data.body: While in Flutter Project: "Launch in a tool window" doesn't work and no emulator menu is showing in the right bar.
Does it work if you use the menu `View > Tool Windows > Emulator` then launch the emulator from the AVD Manager?

I have enabled it here:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15264938/117352071-24451280-aecc-11eb-98a0-4aa07be2c405.png)

And I don't find the `Emulator` option when clicking `View`
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15264938/117352148-3f178700-aecc-11eb-9f53-ac35dd2e48e3.png)

(Note: When I create a plain Android project after Gradle build, the emulator is showing. This problem appears only when I create a project using the flutter plugin. I opened an existing project, and within that project, the emulator is working as expected. The problem seems to be with the new app creating workflow.)
Same issue. Everything worked previously, but a few days ago this problem appeared.

Something has changed in the project template used by the `flutter` tool to generate projects. It appears possible to work around the problem, but it might be risky so proceed with caution. The steps. are: - Open the Project Structure dialog (`File > Project Structure`). - Select `Modules` in the list. - Click the `+` to add a new module of type `Android`. (This view is from a Mac. The `+` may be located elsewhere for Windows. If you have the `Dependencies` tab selected then it will also have a `+` and that one is not what you want.) You don't need to change the defaults. Click `OK`, and you should see the `Emulator` tab appear in the right tool window bar.

> Something has changed in the project template used by the `flutter` tool to generate projects. > > It appears possible to work around the problem, but it might be risky so proceed with caution. > The steps. are: > > * Open the Project Structure dialog (`File > Project Structure`). > * Select `Modules` in the list. > * Click the `+` to add a new module of type `Android`. > > > > (This view is from a Mac. The `+` may be located elsewhere for Windows. If you have the `Dependencies` tab selected then it will also have a `+` and that one is not what you want.) > > You don't need to change the defaults. Click `OK`, and you should see the `Emulator` tab appear in the right tool window bar. I can confirm, it works in a hacky way!
The template files need to be updated. We didn't get to this for the M61 release so moving to M62, since it involves changing the Flutter SDK.
This issue is fixed by upgrading to Bumblebee.
